@DATABASE Help

@NODE Main "AmigaGuideģ Help"
The documents on this disk are displayed using Commodore's "Amiga Guide".

Using the mouse
ĮĮĮĮĮĮĮĮĮĮĮĮĮĮĮ
For mouse use, note the following conventions:

    "click"  =  move the mouse until the mouse pointer is over the desired
                area, then press and release the left mouse button quickly

    "drag"   =  as "click", but press and hold the left mouse button down
                and move the mouse

Documents are split up into subject areas known as "topics". Topics are
chosen simply by clicking on any text which is surrounded by a box.

It is unlikely that the whole of a topic will be able to fit on the screen
at the same time. The amount of the topic which is currently on the screen
is shown by the white rectangular "scroll bar" on the far right of the
screen. You can reveal more of the topic either by dragging this scroll bar
or by clicking the up and down arrows below the scroll bar (try it now!).

Above the topic's text are six "buttons" which perform various functions
when clicked. These functions are:

    Contents -  Selects the contents page.

    (Index   -  Unused by any documents on this disk)

    Help     -  Selects these help pages.

    Retrace  -  Selects the topic previously chosen. Repeated clicking of
                this button "retraces" the topics you have chosen so far.

    Browse   -  These two buttons select the previous and next topic in the
                document you are reading respectively.

When any of these buttons appear checkered, they cannot be selected. (This
checkering is known as "ghosting"). You'll notice that all buttons in this
window are currently ghosted, except "Browse >".

The help file window is closed by clicking its close gadget (the small
gadget on the far upper left of the window).


Using the keyboard
ĮĮĮĮĮĮĮĮĮĮĮĮĮĮĮĮĮĮ
This section describes the keyboard equivalents to the mouse operations
described above. It is likely that you'll wish to mix mouse and keyboard
use when using a document, for maximum speed.

In this list: <up>, <down>, <left> and <right> refer to respective arrow
keys; and (for example) "Shift - <up>" means hold down the Shift key and
press the up arrow key.

    Return          Selects the topic highlighted in blue.

    (Shift)-Tab     Cycles through each topic box currently on the screen,
                    highlighting them in blue.

    <up> or <down>  Scrolls the topic upwards or downwards.

    Shift - <up>    Moves the topic a page upwards.

    Shift - <down>  Moves the topic a page downwards.

    Alt - <up>      Moves the topic to the very top.

    Alt - <down>    Moves the topic to the very bottom.

    Space bar       Scroll forwards

    Backspace       Scroll backwards

Holding down any of these keys listed above repeats the function
continuously.

Alternatively, the various numeric keypad keys (A600 excluded) - Home, End,
Pg Up, Pg Dn, the arrows - can be used to move around a topic.

Note that the six buttons at the top of the screen can be activated from
the keyboard by pressing the key underlined on the gadget. For example, to
select "Retrace", press the R key; to select "Browse >", press the ">" key.


* For a more detailed "reference manual" of Amiga Guide (prepared by
  Commodore themselves), click the Browse > button.

* To remove this help window, click the close button on the far upper left.

@ENDNODE

